1 Background and Aims

The hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA-) axis mediates the long-term stress response by culminating in the release of glucocorticoids, primarily cortisol in humans or corticosterone in rodents (Miller & Auchus, 2011). Stress activates neurons in the paraventricular nucleus (PVN) of the hypothalamus which lead to the release of corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) into the portal vessels. CRH travels to the anterior pituitary and triggers the release of adrenocorticotrope hormone (ACTH), which circulates in the bloodstream to eventually reach the adrenal glands and stimulate the release of glucocorticoids (GCs) into the blood. GCs bind to endogenously expressed glucocorticoid receptors (GRs) to mediate the sustained and genomic stress response (Spencer & Deak, 2016; Spiga et al., 2014). The effects of the stress response are tissue-specific alterations in cellular functioning including, for example, the upregulated expression of key enzymes involved in the hepatic gluconeogenic pathway resulting in increased plasma glucose levels. Thus, increasing available energy resources, enabling the organism to effectively combat an imposed stressor (Cui et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2023).

In the unbound deactivated state, GR predominantly localizes in the cytoplasm as part of a multi-protein complex containing heat shock protein 90 (Hsp90) (Nicolaides et al., 2000). Upon glucocorticoid-binding, it dissociates from the complex, revealing a nuclear localization signal (NLS) which facilitates its nuclear import (Leistner & Menke, 2020; Spencer & Deak, 2016). Activated receptors form hetero- or homodimers which can act as hormone-dependent transcription factors, binding to roughly 15 nucleotide long consensus sequences referred to as glucocorticoid response elements (GREs) (Carrigan et al., 2007; Timmermans et al., 2019). GREs typically reside near promoter regions of glucocorticoid target genes. Once GRs associate with GREs, several co-regulators are recruited which assist GRs in modulating the transcriptional rate of their target genes.

Dexamethasone (DEX) is a synthetic glucocorticoid, a specific GR agonist, known to activate GR (Silva et al., 2014). Reddy et al.(2009) previously identified roughly 4392 genomic positions bound by GR upon DEX treatment (1h, 100nM) and reproduced 89% of GR-binding sites (GBSs) identified by So et al.(2007). This has since been reproduced in further studies (Vockley et al., 2016).

While the spatial dynamics of GR upon activation and the physiological impacts of GR-binding are better understood, the temporal dynamics of GR-binding are less so. Specifically, the ceasing of binding. By analysing GR ChIP-Seq data provided by Reddy and colleagues, we aim to address this and answer the following questions:

  1. Can we identify clusters of genomic regions where GR-binding increases or decreases with sustained DEX-treatment? If so, what are the biological functions predominantly associated with these clusters and are they associated with unique co-factors?

  2. Do the temporal dynamics of GR-binding vary with distance from the transcription start site (TSS)?

  3. Does the speed at which GR-binding is lost over time depend on initial binding strength?

2 Download files

The analysed ChIP-Seq data included a time series treatment of A549 cells with DEX for 30 minutes, 1 hour, 4 hours, and 8 hours. The data included narrowPeak files (for peak calling) and BAM files (for reads counting). BAM files for all isogenic replicates were included to ensure robustness and statistical reliability.

The first step after downloading the data involved merging all GR peaks from the four time points (peaks_30, peaks_1, peaks_4, and peaks_8) into a non-redundant set of 21,137 peaks using the reduce() function in GenomicRanges (v1.60.0). The purpose of this step was to establish a single, unified set of peak coordinates across all four peak objects. This ensures that when building the signal matrix and performing downstream analyses, every sample is quantified at the same genomic positions.

4 Quantify binding signals at consensus peaks

Here we use featureCounts() and .bam files for the alignment, to calculate the counts of our consensus peaks in each replicates

se$sampleID <- colnames(signal_matrix)

We next quantified reads overlapping the consensus peaks (n = 21,137) across 12 replicates (3 per time point) using featureCounts() function in Rsubread (v2.22.1). The number of reads assigned to peaks per time point were as follows:

  • 30 min replicates: 443,8551,031,880 reads (3.25.7% of total)

  • 1 h replicates: 620,164827,587 reads (3.85.2%)

  • 4 h replicates: 210297495,560 reads (1.33.0%)

  • 8 h replicates: 321,140447,624 reads (1.92.8%)

5 Differential analysis of binding activity by edgeR

# edgeR analysis
dge <- DGEList(assay(se, "counts"))
group <- se$Time
design <- model.matrix(~ 0 + group)  #design matrix
rownames(design) <- se$sampleID
contrast <- limma::makeContrasts(early_vs_late = (group30 + group1)/2 - (group4+group8)/2,  #only have one contrast group
                                 levels = design)
  
dge <- calcNormFactors(dge)  #calculate normalization factors
keep <- filterByExpr(dge$counts, min.count = 20, design = design)  # filter out those peaks with very low signal
dge$counts <- dge$counts[keep, ]
se <- se[keep, ]
signal_matrix <- signal_matrix[rownames(se),]
names(consensus_peaks) <- paste0("peak_", seq_len(length(consensus_peaks)))
consensus_peaks <- consensus_peaks[rownames(se),] # make sure that signal matrix and consensus peaks have the same length
# we keep 9477 peaks finally

y <- estimateDisp(dge, design)
fit <- glmFit(y, design)
lrt <- glmLRT(fit, contrast = contrast)
results <- as.data.frame(topTags(lrt, n = Inf))
head(results)
##                logFC   logCPM       LR       PValue          FDR
## peak_2497  -1.807294 7.066099 112.4218 2.888423e-26 2.696343e-22
## peak_16422 -2.834975 5.009106 104.3811 1.669123e-24 7.790632e-21
## peak_446   -1.941531 6.208725 102.4355 4.456412e-24 1.195221e-20
## peak_17608 -1.703210 8.577849 102.1600 5.121461e-24 1.195221e-20
## peak_15605 -2.089166 6.528364 100.4469 1.216143e-23 2.270538e-20
## peak_5923   1.838984 7.309844  94.3539 2.638666e-22 4.105324e-19
# Below we calculate the mean value of each replicates in early/late timepoint for visualization
early_signal <- rowMeans(signal_matrix[, c("gr30_align_1", "gr30_align_2", "gr30_align_3", "gr1_align_1", "gr1_align_2", "gr1_align_3")])
late_signal  <- rowMeans(signal_matrix[, c("gr4_align_1", "gr4_align_2", "gr4_align_3", "gr8_align_1", "gr8_align_2", "gr8_align_3")])
logFC <- results$logFC
names(logFC) <- rownames(results)
# now the order in logFC is not in ascending order of peak number. want to rearrange it:
num <- as.integer(sub("^peak_([0-9]+)$", "\\1", names(logFC)))
order <- order(num)
logFC <- logFC[order]
FDR <- results$FDR
names(FDR) <- rownames(results)
FDR <- FDR[order]
#saveRDS(logFC, "logFC.rds")
# signal decay vs early occupancy
plot(early_signal, logFC,
     xlab = "Early signal (0.5h + 1h avg)",
     ylab = "Log2FC (Late / Early)",
     main = "Initial Occupancy vs Binding Loss",
     pch = 16)

# Add linear regression line
abline(lm(logFC ~ early_signal), col = "red", lwd = 2)
abline(h=0, col="darkblue", lty=2)
# Add correlation results
cor_test_result <- cor.test(early_signal, logFC, method = "pearson") # correlation test to quantify relationship
legend("topright", legend = paste("r =", round(cor_test_result$estimate, 2),
                                  "\np =", signif(cor_test_result$p.value, 3)),
       bty = "n")

In this plot, the x-axis indicates the strength of the initial binding. The larger the signal is, the stronger (or more active) binding it is. The y-axis indicates the difference in binding activity in the early timepoint comparing to the late timepoint. A small but significant positive correlation (r = 0.11, p = 2.2e-26) was observed, suggesting that with stronger (or more active) binding at early timepoint, the difference between early and late timepoint is greater.

# clustering the regions based on logFC and FDR
mcols(consensus_peaks)$FDR <- FDR
mcols(consensus_peaks)$logFC <- logFC
# Create logFC-based groups (manual thresholds)
logFC_groups <- ifelse(mcols(consensus_peaks)$logFC > 1 & mcols(consensus_peaks)$FDR < 0.05, "Decreasing",
                 ifelse(mcols(consensus_peaks)$logFC < -1 & mcols(consensus_peaks)$FDR < 0.05, "Increasing", "Stable"))

# Turn into a factor
logFC_groups <- factor(logFC_groups, levels = c("Decreasing", "Stable", "Increasing"))
mcols(consensus_peaks)$logFC_group <- logFC_groups
# Check counts
table(logFC_groups)
## logFC_groups
## Decreasing     Stable Increasing 
##        365       8593        377

Visualize in histogram

# Plot distribution of logFC 
df <- data.frame(logFC = logFC, Group = logFC_groups)

ggplot(df, aes(x = logFC, fill = Group)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Decreasing" = "blue", "Stable" = "gray", "Increasing" = "red")) +
  labs(title = "GR Binding Change: Early vs Late", x = "log2 Fold Change", y = "Number of regions")

All dynamic genomic regions, ordered by logFC groups

library(pheatmap)
library(RColorBrewer)

# Normalize signal matrix by z-score (rows)
signal_matrix_z <- t(scale(t(signal_matrix)))
# Order all rows by logFC group
order_all <- order(logFC_groups)
signal_ordered_all <- as.data.frame(signal_matrix_z[order_all, ])
annotation_ordered_all <- data.frame(Cluster = logFC_groups[order_all])
rownames(annotation_ordered_all) <- rownames(signal_ordered_all)

# Colors for groups (only plot significantly changed peaks)
ann_colors <- list(Cluster = c("Decreasing" = "blue", "Increasing" = "red"))
signal_ordered_all$label <- annotation_ordered_all$Cluster 
# only plot increasing and decreasing peaks
pheatmap(signal_ordered_all[signal_ordered_all$label!="Stable",c(1:12)],
         cluster_rows = FALSE,
         cluster_cols = FALSE,
         annotation_row = annotation_ordered_all,
         annotation_colors = ann_colors,
         show_rownames = FALSE,
         color = colorRampPalette(rev(brewer.pal(9, "RdYlBu")))(100),
         main = "All Changing Regions Ordered by Binding Change (logFC Group)")

Using edgeR (v4.6.2), we conducted a differential binding analysis comparing early (30 min and 1 h) versus late (4 h and 8 h) time points. After filtering out low-signal peaks, we retained 9,477 peaks from the original 21,137.

For each peak, the log fold-change (logFC) and FDR was calculated. Based on logFC and FDR values, peaks were categorized as follows:

  • Decreasing: FDR < 0.05 and logFC > 1 (n = 365)

  • Increasing: FDR < 0.05 logFC < -1 (n = 377)

  • Stable: FDR >= 0.05 or -1 < logFC < -1 (n = 8,593)

Peaks showing a decrease in binding over time (n = 365) represent early GR-binding sites that diminish as treatment progresses. In contrast, increasing peaks (n = 377) reflect an increase in the number of GR-binding events at later time points (4 h and 8 h). Most peaks (n = 8,593) were classified as stable, indicating consistent GR-binding across the time course.

These results suggest that most peaks show early binding which remains stable over time, with only a few gaining or losing binding at later stages. This pattern is also evident in the scatter plot, which shows early occupied sites declining and late-specific sites emerging. The histogram further illustrates this observation, showing a near-symmetrical distribution of increasing (n = 377) and decreasing (n = 365) peaks. The heatmap reflects a similar trend.

To associate biological functions with GRs temporal binding patterns, we performed a gene ontology enrichment analysis using rGREAT (v.2.10.0) for each of the three peak categories (increasing, decreasing, and stable). Each group exhibited distinct functional signatures, highlighting the biological relevance of GRs dynamic binding over time.

For the decreasing GR-binding cluster, the top enriched terms included:

  • Animal organ morphogenesis (Fold enrichment 2.25)

  • Regulation of anatomical structure morphogenesis (Fold enrichment 2.10)

For the increasing GR-binding cluster, the most enriched terms were:

  • Regulation of developmental process (Fold enrichment 1.75)

  • Regulation of cell differentiation (Fold enrichment 1.60)

The stable GR-binding cluster showed enrichment for:

  • Anatomical structure morphogenesis (Fold enrichment 1.30)

  • Regulation of multicellular organismal process (Fold enrichment 1.25)

Overall developmental terms seem to dominate in the increasing cluster, whereas morphogenic terms are stronger in the decreasing cluster. Terms found in the stable cluster are more associated with maintaining basic cellular functions. One term found in all three clusters is the regulation of multicellular organismal processes.

7 Distance to Transcription Start Site (TSS)

# Load TxDb
txdb <- TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene
# Extract TSS positions as GRanges
tss <- promoters(genes(txdb), upstream=0, downstream=1)
##   2169 genes were dropped because they have exons located on both strands of
##   the same reference sequence or on more than one reference sequence, so cannot
##   be represented by a single genomic range.
##   Use 'single.strand.genes.only=FALSE' to get all the genes in a GRangesList
##   object, or use suppressMessages() to suppress this message.
peaks_list <- list(decreasing = peaks_decreasing,
                   increasing = peaks_increasing,
                   stable = peaks_stable)
# Calculate distance to nearest TSS per peak, add cluster info
distances_df <- do.call(rbind, lapply(names(peaks_list), function(cluster_name) {
  peaks <- peaks_list[[cluster_name]]
  nearest_tss <- distanceToNearest(peaks, tss)
  data.frame(distance = mcols(nearest_tss)$distance, cluster = cluster_name)
}))
# Plot distance distributions
ggplot(distances_df, aes(x = cluster, y = distance)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_log10() +  # distances are often skewed; log scale helps
  labs(y = "Distance to nearest TSS (log scale)", x = "Cluster",
       title = "Distance to TSS by Cluster")
## Warning in scale_y_log10(): log-10 transformation introduced infinite values.
## Warning: Removed 250 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).

We measured the distance of each cluster to transcription factor start sites (TSSs) in order to understand if temporal dynamics of GR-binding vary with distance from the TSS. Out of the three clusters, GR-binding sites from the increasing cluster show the tightest distribution. This low variability in distance to TSS suggests that they are potentially more focused around promoter regions. The decreasing cluster shows a wider distribution followed by the stable cluster which has the widest distribution and many outliers, probably including very distal regulatory elements. All three clusters show a comparable median making no cluster appear dramatically closer or farther from TSS.

10 Discussion

In this study, we characterized the temporal dynamics of glucocorticoid receptor (GR)- binding in A549 cells in response to sustained Dexamethasone (DEX) treatment using publicly available ChIP-seq data. By comparing GR-binding at 0.5, 1, 4, and 8 hours post-treatment, we identified increasing, decreasing, and stable GR-DNA interactions over time. These findings provide new insight into the timing and regulation of GR-mediated transcription.

The vast majority of GR-binding sites (~90%) were stable across all time points, suggesting that a core set of GR target regions remain persistently occupied. However, approximately 7% of peaks showed dynamic behaviour, with roughly equal numbers of peaks showing increased or decreased binding over time. Gene ontology enrichment analysis of these dynamic clusters revealed the biological relevance potentially tied to these shifts. Notably, increasing peaks were enriched for terms related to developmental processes and cell differentiation, suggesting that GR engages these pathways more at later time points, possibly to initiate or reinforce longer-term cell state transitions in response to glucocorticoids. In contrast, decreasing peaks were enriched for morphogenetic processes, potentially reflecting an early wave of GR-binding which may initiate signaling cascades involved in tissue remodeling or structural reorganization.

Interestingly, motif enrichment analysis revealed that, in addition to GRs canonical NR3C1 motif, transcription factors such as MAX and JUND were globally enriched across all peaks and are likely involved in co-regulating GR-bound sites. This finding is consistent with several other studies (Dang, 2012; Herrlich, 2001; Mamoor, 2020; Poole & Van Riggelen, 2017; Weikum et al., 2017). Specifically, Vockley et al.(2016) and Reddy et al.(2012) also report overlap of GR and JUND upon DEX treatment. JUND is a member of the AP-1 (Activator Protein-1) transcription factor complex and forms homo- or heterodimers. It primarily works to limit the immune systems response by regulating genes for proliferation, apoptosis, and differentiation. Further, it can either have a pro- or anti-oncogenic effect and may provide protection against apoptosis induced by oxidative stress. It has been reported to associate with GR via protein-protein interactions a mechanism dubbed trans-repression (Herrlich, 2001; Weikum et al., 2017). While JUND facilitates GR-binding at certain genomic sites by tethering GR to the AP-1 complex rather than through direct DNA binding, GR can, in turn, repress JUNDs transcriptional activity.(Herrlich, 2001; Vockley et al.; Weikum et al., 2017). MAX reportedly primarily associates with GR indirectly, for example via the RNA-binding protein hnRNP U (Mamoor, 2020). MAX, short for MYC-associated factor X, is a small, ubiquitously expressed protein which forms heterodimers primarily with MYC, a basic helix-loop-helix leucine zipper (bHLH-Zip) transcription factor involved in processes including growth, differentiation and apoptosis (Poole & Van Riggelen, 2017). Overactive MYC/MAX signalling is associated with several cancers. However, when bound with MXD, also known as MAD, family members, MAX suppresses MYC activity and thus prevents oncogenesis (Dang, 2012; Poole & Van Riggelen, 2017).

Motif scanning for JUND and MAX across the increasing and decreasing GR-binding clusters revealed a stable enrichment of MAX across both clusters (3.5% and 3.6% overlap respectively). JUND showed greater enrichment in the decreasing cluster with 60% overlap compared to 15.6% overlap with peaks from the increasing cluster. A minimal but consistent association of MAX with GR-peaks across both clusters regardless of whether GR-binding is decreasing or increasing, could suggest a foundational role of MAX, including possibly the maintenance of chromatin accessibility or serving as a scaffold for other regulatory complexes. While MAX seems to operate in a context-independent manner in regards to GR-binding, JUND appears to be dynamically recruited to sites where GR-binding decreases with time compared to sites where GR-binding increases. Increased GR seems to displace or repress JUND, but it may re-bind as GR-binding fades. This suggests it may possibly be acting more as a context-specific co-regulator, potentially trans-repressed by GR, as also previously reported.

Our analysis of GR-peak proximity toTSSs revealed differences in its spatial distribution across clusters. Peaks associated with increased GR-binding tended to be more proximal to TSSs, while stable and decreasing peaks were more widely distributed across also many distal regulatory elements. This suggests that later GR-binding events may rely more on promoter-proximal interactions, whereas early binding sites may be regulated to a greater extent by enhancer elements, which are known to impact transcription of their target genes also from a distance. Despite the differences in distribution, all three clusters show similar distances on average, as indicated by their comparable medians.

Finally, we observed a weak but significant correlation between initial GR-binding strength and persistence, indicating that strongly bound GR sites are marginally more likely to be retained over time. However, the effect size was small, accounting for only a minor portion of the observed variance. This weak correlation suggests that additional factors beyond initial binding strength, for example chromatin remodeling, cofactor recruitment, or local histone modifications likely also play a critical role in determining the duration of GR-binding.

There are some limitations to this study. Firstly, the analysis was based on bulk ChIP-seq data, which averages the signal across a population of cells and may hide cell-to-cell differences in GR-binding dynamics. Secondly, analysing just one cell line (A549) limits the generalizability of the results to other cell types or physiological contexts. Finally, while motif analysis can indicate potential co-regulators, functional validation (e.g., through knockdown or co-ChIP experiments) would be needed to confirm their involvement.

11 Conclusion

Our time-resolved analysis of GR-binding in response to DEX treatment reveals distinct temporal clusters of GR-DNA interactions, each associated with different genomic, functional, and spatial features. While most GR-binding events are stable over time, a subset exhibits dynamic gain or loss of occupancy. These subsets correlate with unique biological pathways and co-factors. Distance between GR-binding site and TSS does not significantly correlate with GR-binding activity. Together, these findings highlight the complexity of GR-mediated transcriptional regulation and highlight the need for further temporally resolved analyses to fully understand hormone receptor dynamics. Future studies integrating chromatin accessibility, cofactor binding, and transcriptional output will be essential to decode the complex regulation of glucocorticoid signaling.

12 Method

12.1 Data Preparation

The peak files were obtained from the ENCODE Project. Specifically, ChIPseq narrowPeak files for treatment at 30 min (ENCFF443TPX), 1 h (ENCFF395FIP), 4 h (ENCFF995VAB) and 8 h (ENCFF791HTJ) were downloaded in BED format. Package rtracklayer (v1.68.0) was used for peak calling. reduce() in GenomicRanges (v1.60.0) was used to create a non-redundant consensus peak set. BAM files were downloaded from the same experiment for alignment using featureCounts() function in Rsubread (v2.22.1). After the alignment, we got the counts matrix including all consensus peaks for downstream analysis.

12.2 Differential Analysis

The package edgeR (v4.6.2) with glmFit() function was used to apply the model and test for significance. The increasing peaks are defined as logFC < 1 and FDR < 0.05, while the decreasing peaks are defined as logFC > 1 and FDR < 0.05. The rest of the peaks are then defined as stable peaks.

12.3 Functional Enrichment Analysis

rGREAT (v.2.10.0) was used for gene ontology analysis. For each peak cluster, the top 10 GO Biological Process terms were selected for visualization.

12.4 Distance to TSS

TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene (v3.21.0) was used as the reference genome to extract the position of TSSs. The function distanceToNearest() in package GenomicRanges (v1.60.0) was used to calculate the distance between peak and the nearest TSS.

12.5 Motif Enrichment Analysis and Scanning

All the consensus peaks were resized to the same width 500bp. AH106285 in AnnotationHub was used as the reference genome. PWMEnrich (v4.44.0) was used for motif enrichment analysis with PWMEnrich.Hsapiens.background as the background; motifmatchr (v1.30.0) was used for motif scanning.
